  9  /-! # Filter bases
 10  
 11  In this file we define `filter.has_basis l p s`, where `l` is a filter on `Î±`, `p` is a predicate
 12  on some index set `Î¹`, and `s : Î¹ â†’ set Î±`.
 13  
 14  ## Main statements
 15  
 16  * `has_basis.mem_iff`, `has_basis.mem_of_superset`, `has_basis.mem_of_mem` : restate `t âˆˆ f` in terms
 17    of a basis;
 18  * `basis_sets` : all sets of a filter form a basis;
 19  * `has_basis.inf`, `has_basis.inf_principal`, `has_basis.prod`, `has_basis.prod_self`,
 20    `has_basis.map`, `has_basis.comap` : combinators to construct filters of `l âŠ“ l'`,
 21    `l âŠ“ principal t`, `l.prod l'`, `l.prod l`, `l.map f`, `l.comap f` respectively;
 22  * `has_basis.le_iff`, `has_basis.ge_iff`, has_basis.le_basis_iff` : restate `l â‰¤ l'` in terms
 23    of bases.
 24  * `has_basis.tendsto_right_iff`, `has_basis.tendsto_left_iff`, `has_basis.tendsto_iff` : restate
 25    `tendsto f l l'` in terms of bases.
 26  
 27  ## Implementation notes
 28  
 29  As with `Union`/`bUnion`/`sUnion`, there are three different approaches to filter bases:
 30  
 31  * `has_basis l s`, `s : set (set Î±)`;
 32  * `has_basis l s`, `s : Î¹ â†’ set Î±`;
 33  * `has_basis l p s`, `p : Î¹ â†’ Prop`, `s : Î¹ â†’ set Î±`.
 34  
 35  We use the latter one because, e.g., `ğ“ x` in an `emetric_space` or in a `metric_space` has a basis
 36  of this form. The other two can be emulated using `s = id` or `p = Î» _, true`.
 37  
 38  With this approach sometimes one needs to `simp` the statement provided by the `has_basis`
 39  machinery, e.g., `simp only [exists_prop, true_and]` or `simp only [forall_const]` can help
 40  with the case `p = Î» _, true`.
